Ruth IgielnikStaff editor, polling

In recent weeks, President Trump has taken a series of actions that have irritated or even angered his base. More than one-third of Republicans disapprove of how he handled the files related to Jeffrey Epstein, according to a recent poll from Quinnipiac University. And among voters who approve of Trump’s job performance, 41 percent think he has not gone far enough in reducing everyday prices.

But that doesn’t mean his supporters are breaking with him. His numbers have remained particularly strong with Republicans, around 90 percent of whom continue to approve of his job performance. And 93 percent of Trump approvers say his approach has been necessary to shake up things in Washington.

Compare with past presidents

These charts show how President Trump’s net approval rating compares with the net approval of past presidents. Net approval is the percentage of survey respondents who approve of the president minus the percentage who disapprove.

Irineo CabrerosStaff editor, statistical modeling

It is typical for new presidents to experience a decline in support in the first few months of their presidencies. Trump’s approval rating has been dropping slightly faster than those of his recent predecessors, but the pace of the decline is not unprecedented.

Ruth IgielnikStaff editor, polling

It is not uncommon for polls to show a fairly broad range of support on an issue. Results can vary because of the inherent challenges of polling — surveys can only be expected to be accurate within a couple of percentage points — or because polls were conducted using different methods and at different times. One of the reasons examining an average of polls can be so useful is it can balance out these differences and make it easier to analyze change over time.

By Irineo Cabreros, Annie Daniel, Jon Huang, Ruth Igielnik, Jasmine C. Lee, Alex Lemonides, Ilana Marcus, Dan Simmons-Ritchie, Jonah Smith, Albert Sun and Rumsey Taylor. Additional work by Andrew Chavez and Isaac White.

See more on: Donald Trump

The Latest on the Trump Administration

  • Air Force and Transgender Men and Women: At least a dozen transgender men and women serving in the U.S. Air Force who had applied for early retirement to avoid being kicked out of the service for their gender identity have had their retirement approval rescinded by the service.

  • Foreign Drug Cartels: President Trump has secretly signed a directive to the Pentagon to begin using military force against certain Latin American drug cartels that his administration has deemed terrorist organizations, according to people familiar with the matter.

  • Trump’s Role on Jan. 6: The Smithsonian put up new text that changed its description of President Trump’s impeachment following the Jan. 6, 2021, attack on the Capitol.

  • Escalating Pressure Campaign: The Justice Department this week escalated its pressure campaign on Letitia James, New York’s attorney general and one of President Trump’s longtime adversaries, opening a civil rights investigation into her office and appointing a special prosecutor to scrutinize her real estate dealings.

  • Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac: Seventeen years after the financial crisis, the Trump administration is looking to sell shares of the companies in what could be a step toward freeing the mortgage finance firms from full federal control.

  • Campaign for a Pardon: A sophisticated operation is pushing Trump to forgive Changpeng Zhao, which would boost the chances for his company, Binance, to break into the U.S. market.

  • Bird Death Crackdown: Critics accused the administration of a double standard, trying to stop wind projects because of potential bald eagle deaths while easing rules for oil and gas companies.

Hundreds of readers asked about our coverage of the president. Times editors and reporters responded to some of the most common questions.
